defs.docs:
Consumes and leaks the `Box`, returning a mutable reference,
 `&'a mut T`. Note that the type `T` must outlive the chosen lifetime
 `'a`. If the type has only static references, or none at all, then this
 may be chosen to be `'static`.

defs.name: with_capacity
defs.docs:
Creates an empty `BinaryHeap` with a specific capacity.
 This preallocates enough memory for `capacity` elements,
 so that the `BinaryHeap` does not have to be reallocated
 until it contains at least that many values.

defs.name: peek_mut
defs.docs:
Returns a mutable reference to the greatest item in the binary heap, or
 `None` if it is empty.

defs.name: pop
defs.docs:
Removes the greatest item from the binary heap and returns it, or `None` if it
 is empty.

defs.name: push
defs.docs: Pushes an item onto the binary heap.

defs.name: into_sorted_vec
defs.docs:
Consumes the `BinaryHeap` and returns a vector in sorted
 (ascending) order.

defs.name: append
defs.docs: Moves all the elements of `other` into `self`, leaving `other` empty.

defs.name: iter
defs.docs:
Returns an iterator visiting all values in the underlying vector, in
 arbitrary order.

defs.name: peek
defs.docs: Returns the greatest item in the binary heap, or `None` if it is empty.

defs.name: capacity
defs.docs: Returns the number of elements the binary heap can hold without reallocating.

defs.name: reserve_exact
defs.docs:
Reserves the minimum capacity for exactly `additional` more elements to be inserted in the
 given `BinaryHeap`. Does nothing if the capacity is already sufficient.

defs.name: reserve
defs.docs:
Reserves capacity for at least `additional` more elements to be inserted in the
 `BinaryHeap`. The collection may reserve more space to avoid frequent reallocations.

defs.name: shrink_to_fit
defs.docs: Discards as much additional capacity as possible.

defs.name: shrink_to
defs.docs: Discards capacity with a lower bound.

defs.name: into_vec
defs.docs:
Consumes the `BinaryHeap` and returns the underlying vector
 in arbitrary order.

defs.name: len

defs.name: is_empty
defs.docs: Checks if the binary heap is empty.

defs.name: drain
defs.docs: Clears the binary heap, returning an iterator over the removed elements.

defs.name: clear
defs.docs: Drops all items from the binary heap.

defs.name: Drain

defs.name: Root
defs.docs:
An owned tree. Note that despite being owned, this does not have a destructor,
 and must be cleaned up manually.

defs.name: as_mut
defs.value: fn (&mut self) -> NodeRef<marker::Mut<'_>, K, V, marker::LeafOrInternal>

defs.name: push_level
defs.value: fn (&mut self) -> NodeRef<marker::Mut<'_>, K, V, marker::Internal>
defs.docs:
Adds a new internal node with a single edge, pointing to the previous root, and make that
 new node the root. This increases the height by 1 and is the opposite of `pop_level`.

defs.name: pop_level
defs.docs:
Removes the root node, using its first child as the new root. This cannot be called when
 the tree consists only of a leaf node. As it is intended only to be called when the root
 has only one edge, no cleanup is done on any of the other children are elements of the root.
 This decreases the height by 1 and is the opposite of `push_level`.

defs.name: NodeRef
defs.docs: A reference to a node.

defs.name: len
defs.docs:
Finds the length of the node. This is the number of keys or values. In an
 internal node, the number of edges is `len() + 1`.

defs.name: height
defs.docs:
Returns the height of this node in the whole tree. Zero height denotes the
 leaf level.

defs.name: forget_type
defs.docs:
Removes any static information about whether this node is a `Leaf` or an
 `Internal` node.

defs.name: ascend
defs.value:
fn (self) -> Result<Handle<NodeRef<BorrowType, K, V, marker::Internal>, marker::Edge>,
       Self>
defs.docs:
Finds the parent of the current node. Returns `Ok(handle)` if the current
 node actually has a parent, where `handle` points to the edge of the parent
 that points to the current node. Returns `Err(self)` if the current node has
 no parent, giving back the original `NodeRef`.

defs.name: first_kv
defs.docs: Note that `self` must be nonempty.

defs.name: last_kv
defs.docs: Note that `self` must be nonempty.

defs.name: deallocate_and_ascend
defs.value: fn (self) -> Option<Handle<NodeRef<marker::Owned, K, V, marker::Internal>, marker::Edge>>
defs.docs:
Similar to `ascend`, gets a reference to a node's parent node, but also
 deallocate the current node in the process. This is unsafe because the
 current node will still be accessible despite being deallocated.

defs.name: deallocate_and_ascend
defs.value: fn (self) -> Option<Handle<NodeRef<marker::Owned, K, V, marker::Internal>, marker::Edge>>
defs.docs:
Similar to `ascend`, gets a reference to a node's parent node, but also
 deallocate the current node in the process. This is unsafe because the
 current node will still be accessible despite being deallocated.

defs.name: into_root_mut
defs.docs:
Gets a mutable reference to the root itself. This is useful primarily when the
 height of the tree needs to be adjusted. Never call this on a reborrowed pointer.

defs.name: push
defs.value: fn (&mut self, key: K, val: V) -> ()
defs.docs: Adds a key/value pair the end of the node.

defs.name: push_front
defs.value: fn (&mut self, key: K, val: V) -> ()
defs.docs: Adds a key/value pair to the beginning of the node.

defs.name: push
defs.value: fn (&mut self, key: K, val: V, edge: Root<K, V>) -> ()

Adds a key/value pair and an edge to go to the right of that pair to

defs.name: push_front
defs.value: fn (&mut self, key: K, val: V, edge: Root<K, V>) -> ()
defs.docs:
Adds a key/value pair and an edge to go to the left of that pair to

defs.name: pop
defs.docs:
Removes a key/value pair from the end of this node. If this is an internal node,
 also removes the edge that was to the right of that pair.

defs.name: pop_front
defs.docs:
Removes a key/value pair from the beginning of this node. If this is an internal node,
 also removes the edge that was to the left of that pair.

defs.name: Handle
defs.docs:
A reference to a specific key/value pair or edge within a node. The `Node` parameter
 must be a `NodeRef`, while the `Type` can either be `KV` (signifying a handle on a key/value
 pair) or `Edge` (signifying a handle on an edge).

defs.docs: Creates a new handle to a key/value pair in `node`. `idx` must be less than `node.len()`.

Inserts a new key/value pair between the key/value pairs to the right and left of
 this edge. This method splits the node if there isn't enough room.

Inserts a new key/value pair and an edge that will go to the right of that new pair

 the node if there isn't enough room.

defs.name: descend
defs.docs: Finds the node pointed to by this edge.

defs.value: fn (mut self) -> (NodeRef<marker::Mut<'a>, K, V, marker::Leaf>, K, V, Root<K, V>)
defs.docs: Splits the underlying node into three parts:

defs.value: fn (mut self) -> (Handle<NodeRef<marker::Mut<'a>, K, V, marker::Leaf>, marker::Edge>, K, V)
defs.docs:
Removes the key/value pair pointed to by this handle, returning the edge between the
 now adjacent key/value pairs to the left and right of this handle.

defs.name: split
defs.value: fn (mut self) -> (NodeRef<marker::Mut<'a>, K, V, marker::Internal>, K, V, Root<K, V>)
defs.docs: Splits the underlying node into three parts:

defs.name: can_merge
defs.docs:
Returns `true` if it is valid to call `.merge()`, i.e., whether there is enough room in
 a node to hold the combination of the nodes to the left and right of this handle along
 with the key/value pair at this handle.

defs.name: merge
defs.value: fn (mut self) -> Handle<NodeRef<marker::Mut<'a>, K, V, marker::Internal>, marker::Edge>
defs.docs:
Combines the node immediately to the left of this handle, the key/value pair pointed
 to by this handle, and the node immediately to the right of this handle into one new
 child of the underlying node, returning an edge referencing that new child.

defs.name: steal_left
defs.docs:
This removes a key/value pair from the left child and replaces it with the key/value pair
 pointed to by this handle while pushing the old key/value pair of this handle into the right
 child.

defs.name: steal_right
defs.docs:
This removes a key/value pair from the right child and replaces it with the key/value pair
 pointed to by this handle while pushing the old key/value pair of this handle into the left
 child.

defs.name: bulk_steal_left
defs.docs: This does stealing similar to `steal_left` but steals multiple elements at once.

defs.name: bulk_steal_right
defs.docs: The symmetric clone of `bulk_steal_left`.

defs.name: append
defs.docs: Moves all elements from `other` into `Self`, leaving `other` empty.

defs.name: range
defs.value: fn <T, R> (&self, range: R) -> Range<'_, K, V>
defs.docs:
Constructs a double-ended iterator over a sub-range of elements in the map.
 The simplest way is to use the range syntax `min..max`, thus `range(min..max)` will
 yield elements from min (inclusive) to max (exclusive).
 The range may also be entered as `(Bound<T>, Bound<T>)`, so for example
 `range((Excluded(4), Included(10)))` will yield a left-exclusive, right-inclusive
 range from 4 to 10.

defs.name: range_mut
defs.value: fn <T, R> (&mut self, range: R) -> RangeMut<'_, K, V>
defs.docs:
Constructs a mutable double-ended iterator over a sub-range of elements in the map.
 The simplest way is to use the range syntax `min..max`, thus `range(min..max)` will
 yield elements from min (inclusive) to max (exclusive).
 The range may also be entered as `(Bound<T>, Bound<T>)`, so for example
 `range((Excluded(4), Included(10)))` will yield a left-exclusive, right-inclusive
 range from 4 to 10.

defs.name: range
defs.value: fn <K, R> (&self, range: R) -> Range<'_, T>
defs.docs:
Constructs a double-ended iterator over a sub-range of elements in the set.
 The simplest way is to use the range syntax `min..max`, thus `range(min..max)` will
 yield elements from min (inclusive) to max (exclusive).
 The range may also be entered as `(Bound<T>, Bound<T>)`, so for example
 `range((Excluded(4), Included(10)))` will yield a left-exclusive, right-inclusive
 range from 4 to 10.

defs.name: difference
defs.value: fn <'a> (&'a self, other: &'a BTreeSet<T>) -> Difference<'a, T>
defs.docs:
Visits the values representing the difference,
 i.e., the values that are in `self` but not in `other`,
 in ascending order.

defs.name: symmetric_difference
defs.value: fn <'a> (&'a self, other: &'a BTreeSet<T>) -> SymmetricDifference<'a, T>
defs.docs:
Visits the values representing the symmetric difference,
 i.e., the values that are in `self` or in `other` but not in both,
 in ascending order.

defs.name: intersection
defs.value: fn <'a> (&'a self, other: &'a BTreeSet<T>) -> Intersection<'a, T>
defs.docs:
Visits the values representing the intersection,
 i.e., the values that are both in `self` and `other`,
 in ascending order.

defs.name: union
defs.value: fn <'a> (&'a self, other: &'a BTreeSet<T>) -> Union<'a, T>
defs.docs:
Visits the values representing the union,
 i.e., all the values in `self` or `other`, without duplicates,
 in ascending order.

defs.name: RawVec
defs.docs:
A low-level utility for more ergonomically allocating, reallocating, and deallocating
 a buffer of memory on the heap without having to worry about all the corner cases
 involved. This type is excellent for building your own data structures like Vec and VecDeque.
 In particular:

defs.name: new_in
defs.docs:
Like `new` but parameterized over the choice of allocator for
 the returned RawVec.

defs.name: with_capacity_in
defs.docs:
Like `with_capacity` but parameterized over the choice of
 allocator for the returned RawVec.

defs.name: with_capacity_zeroed_in
defs.docs:
Like `with_capacity_zeroed` but parameterized over the choice
 of allocator for the returned RawVec.

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Creates the biggest possible RawVec (on the system heap)
 without allocating. If T has positive size, then this makes a
 RawVec with capacity 0. If T has 0 size, then it makes a
 RawVec with capacity `usize::MAX`. Useful for implementing
 delayed allocation.

defs.name: with_capacity
defs.docs:
Creates a RawVec (on the system heap) with exactly the
 capacity and alignment requirements for a `[T; cap]`. This is
 equivalent to calling RawVec::new when `cap` is 0 or T is
 zero-sized. Note that if `T` is zero-sized this means you will
 *not* get a RawVec with the requested capacity!

defs.name: with_capacity_zeroed
defs.docs: Like `with_capacity` but guarantees the buffer is zeroed.

defs.name: from_raw_parts_in
defs.value: fn (ptr: *mut T, cap: usize, a: A) -> Self
defs.docs: Reconstitutes a RawVec from a pointer, capacity, and allocator.

defs.docs: Reconstitutes a RawVec from a pointer, capacity.

defs.name: from_box
defs.docs: Converts a `Box<[T]>` into a `RawVec<T>`.

defs.name: ptr
defs.docs:
Gets a raw pointer to the start of the allocation. Note that this is
 Unique::empty() if `cap = 0` or T is zero-sized. In the former case, you must
 be careful.

defs.name: cap
defs.docs: Gets the capacity of the allocation.

defs.name: alloc
defs.docs: Returns a shared reference to the allocator backing this RawVec.

defs.docs: Returns a mutable reference to the allocator backing this RawVec.

Doubles the size of the type's backing allocation. This is common enough
 to want to do that it's easiest to just have a dedicated method. Slightly
 more efficient logic can be provided for this than the general case.

defs.name: try_reserve_exact
defs.value: fn (&mut self, used_cap: usize, needed_extra_cap: usize) -> Result<(), CollectionAllocErr>
defs.docs: The same as `reserve_exact`, but returns on errors instead of panicking or aborting.

defs.name: reserve_exact
defs.value: fn (&mut self, used_cap: usize, needed_extra_cap: usize) -> ()
defs.docs:
Ensures that the buffer contains at least enough space to hold
 `used_cap + needed_extra_cap` elements. If it doesn't already,
 will reallocate the minimum possible amount of memory necessary.
 Generally this will be exactly the amount of memory necessary,
 but in principle the allocator is free to give back more than
 we asked for.

defs.name: try_reserve
defs.value: fn (&mut self, used_cap: usize, needed_extra_cap: usize) -> Result<(), CollectionAllocErr>
defs.docs: The same as `reserve`, but returns on errors instead of panicking or aborting.

defs.name: reserve
defs.value: fn (&mut self, used_cap: usize, needed_extra_cap: usize) -> ()
defs.docs:
Ensures that the buffer contains at least enough space to hold
 `used_cap + needed_extra_cap` elements. If it doesn't already have
 enough capacity, will reallocate enough space plus comfortable slack
 space to get amortized `O(1)` behavior. Will limit this behavior
 if it would needlessly cause itself to panic.

defs.name: reserve_in_place
defs.value: fn (&mut self, used_cap: usize, needed_extra_cap: usize) -> bool
defs.docs:
Attempts to ensure that the buffer contains at least enough space to hold
 `used_cap + needed_extra_cap` elements. If it doesn't already have
 enough capacity, will reallocate in place enough space plus comfortable slack
 space to get amortized `O(1)` behavior. Will limit this behaviour
 if it would needlessly cause itself to panic.

defs.docs:
Shrinks the allocation down to the specified amount. If the given amount

defs.name: try_reserve
defs.value: fn (&mut self, additional: usize) -> Result<(), CollectionAllocErr>
defs.docs:
Tries to reserve capacity for at least `additional` more elements to be inserted
 in the given `String`. The collection may reserve more space to avoid
 frequent reallocations. After calling `reserve`, capacity will be
 greater than or equal to `self.len() + additional`. Does nothing if
 capacity is already sufficient.

defs.name: try_reserve_exact
defs.value: fn (&mut self, additional: usize) -> Result<(), CollectionAllocErr>
defs.docs:
Tries to reserves the minimum capacity for exactly `additional` more elements to
 be inserted in the given `String`. After calling `reserve_exact`,
 capacity will be greater than or equal to `self.len() + additional`.
 Does nothing if the capacity is already sufficient.

defs.docs: Constructs a new, empty `Vec<T>`.

defs.docs: Creates a `Vec<T>` directly from the raw components of another vector.

defs.name: capacity
defs.docs:
Returns the number of elements the vector can hold without
 reallocating.

defs.name: reserve
defs.docs:
Reserves capacity for at least `additional` more elements to be inserted
 in the given `Vec<T>`. The collection may reserve more space to avoid
 frequent reallocations. After calling `reserve`, capacity will be
 greater than or equal to `self.len() + additional`. Does nothing if
 capacity is already sufficient.

defs.name: reserve_exact
defs.docs:
Reserves the minimum capacity for exactly `additional` more elements to
 be inserted in the given `Vec<T>`. After calling `reserve_exact`,
 capacity will be greater than or equal to `self.len() + additional`.
 Does nothing if the capacity is already sufficient.

defs.name: try_reserve
defs.value: fn (&mut self, additional: usize) -> Result<(), CollectionAllocErr>
defs.docs:
Tries to reserve capacity for at least `additional` more elements to be inserted
 in the given `Vec<T>`. The collection may reserve more space to avoid
 frequent reallocations. After calling `reserve`, capacity will be
 greater than or equal to `self.len() + additional`. Does nothing if
 capacity is already sufficient.

defs.name: try_reserve_exact
defs.value: fn (&mut self, additional: usize) -> Result<(), CollectionAllocErr>
defs.docs:
Tries to reserves the minimum capacity for exactly `additional` more elements to
 be inserted in the given `Vec<T>`. After calling `reserve_exact`,
 capacity will be greater than or equal to `self.len() + additional`.
 Does nothing if the capacity is already sufficient.
